df[df['Regions']=='NEW TERRITORIES EAST']\

for element in df.Regions.unique():
    region = element

    df[df['Regions']==region]\
    .groupby(['Districts','Age Range'])['Count'].sum()\
    .reset_index()\
    .pivot(index='Age Range', columns='Districts', values='Count')\
    .plot(kind='barh', stacked=True, 
          title=f'Age Range over Count by Districts in region {region} ')

    #plt.grid(zorder=0)
    plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1.0, 0.5))
    plt.xlabel('Count') #xlabel on index
    plt.show()

import ipywidgets as widgets

district = widgets.Dropdown(
    options=df.Districts.unique(),
    #value=df.Districts.unique()[0],
    description='District: ',
    disabled=False,
)

out = widgets.Output()
def district_graph(value):
    district = value

    df[df['Districts']==district]\
    .groupby(['Age Range','Sex'])['Count'].sum()\
    .reset_index()\
    .pivot(index='Age Range', columns='Sex', values='Count')\
    .plot(kind='barh', stacked=True, 
          title=f'Age Range over Count by Sex in district {district}')

    #plt.grid(zorder=0)
    plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1.0, 0.5))
    plt.xlabel('Count') #xlabel on index
    plt.show()

from ipywidgets import interact
display(district)

interact(district_graph,value=district)
